<div class="gem-c-govspeak govuk-govspeak direction-ltr" data-module="govspeak">
      <div class="govspeak">
<div class="call-to-action">
<h2 id="stay-up-to-date">Stay up to date</h2>

<p>The UK will leave the <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> on 31 October. This page tells you how to prepare for Brexit. It will be updated if anything changes, including if a deal is agreed.<br></br>
<br></br>
<a href="https://www.gov.uk/email-signup/?topic=/government/brexit">Sign up for email alerts</a> to get the latest information.</p>
</div>

<p>The UK government has always been clear that we highly value the contributions <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> citizens make to the social, economic and cultural fabric of the UK and that we want them to stay in the UK.</p>

<p>The <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/no-deal-immigration-arrangements-for-eu-citizens-moving-to-the-uk-after-brexit">No deal immigration arrangements for <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> citizens moving to the UK after Brexit policy paper</a> published on 4 September 2019 explains the transitional arrangements for <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> citizens moving to the UK after Brexit if the UK leaves the <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> without a deal.</p>

<h2 id="the-rights-of-eu-citizens-and-their-families-currently-living-in-the-uk-before-the-uk-leaves-the-eu-to-access-social-housing-and-homelessness-assistance">The rights of <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> citizens and their families currently living in the UK before the UK leaves the <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> to access social housing and homelessness assistance</h2>

<p>The rights and status of <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> citizens and their family members living in the UK before the UK leaves the <abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> will remain the same as now. This means they will continue to be eligible to access social housing, including supported housing, and homelessness assistance on the same terms as now.</p>

<p>In order to deliver the government’s policy intent to maintain the status-quo of eligibility for social housing and homelessness assistance, the current eligibility regulations (the Allocation of Housing and Homelessness (Eligibility) (England) Regulations 2006 (S.I. 2006/1294) have been amended by <a rel="external" href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/861/contents/made">The Allocation of Housing and Homelessness (Eligibility) (England) (Amendment) (<abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> Exit) Regulations 2019 (SI 2019/861)</a>. The Amendment Regulations were laid on 16 April and came into force on 7 May 2019.</p>

<p>These regulations clarify the government’s position on access to benefits and services for those granted pre-settled status under the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/settled-status-eu-citizens-families"><abbr title="European Union">EU</abbr> Settlement Scheme</a>.</p>

<p>A letter was sent to all chief executives of local authorities, chief housing officers and chief officers for children’s services in England informing of this change in legislation.</p>

